The paper deals with the computational complexity of identifying dense substructures in graphs, which is a fundamental problem in graph theory and algorithms. The paper uses techniques from parameterized complexity and computational complexity theory, which are typically studied in the sub-categories of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.CC (Computational Complexity), and cs.CG (Computational Geometry). The paper also discusses the relationship between dense substructures and graph minors, which is a topic in the sub-category of cs.GT (Graph Theory). Finally, the paper provides lower bounds based on the Exponential Time Hypothesis (ETH), which is a central conjecture in the sub-category of cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics).
